<HEAD>Britain Says Falklands Exercise Not Intended To Provoke Argentina</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says a weeklong military exercise
in the <LOCATION>Falkland Islands</LOCATION> set to begin <DATE>Monday</DATE> is not intended to
provoke <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>, noting that fewer than 1,000 troops are to take
part.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>, which claims the islands it calls <LOCATION>Malvinas</LOCATION>, lost a
74-day war with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> for their possession in <DATE>1982</DATE> and still has
not formally declared an end to hostilities in the <LOCATION>South Atlantic</LOCATION>.
   A communique <DATE>Thursday</DATE> from <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s Foreign Affairs and
<ORGANIZATION>Defense Ministries</ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> has adopted plans for ``vigilance
and defensive alert'' during the British exercise and, if
necessary, ``will execute corresponding defense plans.'' It did not
elaborate.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Minister of State</ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION>Armed Forces</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Ian Stewart</PERSON>,
told the <ORGANIZATION>House of Commons</ORGANIZATION> <DATE>Thursday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> that fewer than 1,000
troops and only a small number of aircraft would take part in the
exercise, code-named Fire Focus.
   <PERSON>Stewart</PERSON> said the exercise involves an airlift and is part of a
defensive strategy to keep a minimum of troops in the islands about
400 miles east of the southern Argentine coast.
   The <ORGANIZATION>British Defense Ministry</ORGANIZATION> announced last <DATE>June</DATE> that it was
reducing the strength of its Falklands garrison, but refused to
disclose the size of the cut. Published reports at the time said
the move would cut the garrison then consisting of more than 2,500
troops by about 400.
   Britain completed an international airport at <LOCATION>Mount Pleasant</LOCATION>
near the Falklands capital of <ORGANIZATION>Stanley</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>June 1985</DATE>. The airport can
take wide-bodied military jets, enabling <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> to fly in
reinforcements at short notice if necessary.
   <PERSON>Stewart</PERSON> said the development of contingency plans for a massive
airlift had enabled <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> to halve the size of the garrison.
   He gave no figures for the present strength of the costly
garrison but added: ``Such a substantial reduction of the military
presence ... serves to confirm that our purpose is entirely
defensive.''
   A <ORGANIZATION>Defense Ministry</ORGANIZATION> spokesman, who in accordance with British
practice declined to be named, said later: ``We are not intending
to increase the tension down there ... There is nothing significant
about the timing of it (the exercise). It is not meant in any way
to be provocative to <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>.''
   A <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Office</ORGANIZATION> spokesman said <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> recently notified
<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> through Swiss diplomatic channels that the exercise was
purely one of reinforcement.
   Diplomatic ties between <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>, cut during the
<DATE>1982</DATE> war, remain severed.
</TEXT>
