<HEAD>Briton Begins Begins Military Maneuvers In Falklands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> began a 25-day military exercise <DATE>Monday</DATE> to
test its ability to protect the <LOCATION>Falkland Islands</LOCATION> from invasion, the
<ORGANIZATION>Defense Ministry</ORGANIZATION> reported. <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> said its forces would be on
``defensive alert.''
   ``At this stage, it's very much a paper exercise,'' a ministry
spokesman said. ``The exercise will start with intelligence reports
that an enemy is raising the threat level. They will play out a
scenario.''
   An infantry batallion of 600-1,000 soldiers based in <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>
will fly to the <LOCATION>South Atlantic</LOCATION> archipelago <DATE>March 17-18</DATE>, the
spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> claims the islands off its coast, which it calls the
<LOCATION>Malvinas</LOCATION>, and invaded them in <DATE>April 1982</DATE>. <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> sent a naval task
force and won a 74-day war that killed 712 Argentines and 258
Britons.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> says the exercise, called Fire Focus, is purely
defensive. One of its functions will be to test a new <MONEY>$690 million</MONEY>
airport built since the war.
   <PERSON>Ian Stewart</PERSON>, the armed forces minister, said criticism of the
exercise from <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and other Latin American nations resulted
from misunderstanding of its size.
   ``I do not see how something which is purely a defensive
exercise can be seen as provocative,'' he said.
   ``We have to defend the <LOCATION>Falklands</LOCATION>. We had a very unfortunate
experience six years ago. We not only have a right to have a
defensive garrison in the <LOCATION>Falklands</LOCATION>, we have a responsibility to do
so.''
   The exercise, scheduled to end <DATE>March 31</DATE>, is the largest since
the war and the first with reinforcements flown from <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>.
Military units could not be airlifted in <DATE>1982</DATE> because the airport
was inadequate, and the naval force took weeks to reach the islands.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> says the islands are part of its inheritance from
Spanish colonial rule and claims <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> stole them in <DATE>1833</DATE>.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> has refused to discuss sovereignty, declaring that the
1,900 Falkland Islanders prefer to remain British, but <PERSON>Stewart</PERSON>
said: ``In other respects we would like to have more normal
relations with <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>.''
</TEXT>
