<HEAD>Argentina Loan Reportedly Suspended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>International Monetary Fund</ORGANIZATION>
has suspended payment of a <MONEY>$245 million</MONEY> loan to <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> because
the government failed to achieve promised economic reforms during
the <DATE>third quarter</DATE>, according to a report published <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> did not accomplish adequate cuts in its inflation
rate, which was in double digits each month from Juyy to <DATE>September</DATE>,
and the government's fiscal surplus for the period turned out to be
lower than promised, according to a daily financial newspaper, <ORGANIZATION>El
Cronista Comercial</ORGANIZATION>.
   Citing sources in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, the newspaper reported that
<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> can reclaim the <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION> standby loan if it cuts its
government deficit, its inflation rate and the size of the public
sector work force. That would require massive layoffs, the paper
reported.
</TEXT>
