<LEADPARA>  A 40-ton Soviet space station the size of a railroad car tumbled into the
Earth's atmosphere and burned up over Argentina before dawn today, but no
damage or injuries were immediately reported.;    Argentina's government news
agency Telam said pieces of Salyut 7 apparently fell somewhere in the Andes
Mountains, near the Chilean frontier, but no precise location was given.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SOVIET SPACE STATION FALLS, RAINS 'FIRE'
OVER ARGENTINA  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "Salyut 7 triggered a rain of fire when it entered the atmosphere, that
could be seen from several towns in the provinces of <LOCATION>Cordoba</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Buenos Aires</PERSON>,
<PERSON>Mendoza</PERSON>, <LOCATION>San Luis</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Neuquen</LOCATION> and Chubut," said Telam.;    The Argentine air
force said it had no information on where Salyut 7 may have fallen. There were
no immediate reports of damage or injuries.;    The official Soviet news
agency <ORGANIZATION>Tass</ORGANIZATION> said Salyut 7 and an attached spacecraft re-entered the atmosphere
over a sparsely populated area of central <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> at <TIME>12:47 a.m. local time</TIME>
(<TIME>7:47 p.m. PST</TIME> <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>).;    The <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Space Command</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Colorado Springs</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Colo.</LOCATION>, said the spacecraft was traveling about 17,000 mph at re-entry.;   
Salyut 7 was put into orbit in <DATE>April 1982</DATE>. Tass said it should have stayed in
orbit several more years but a sudden increase in solar activity in <DATE>1988</DATE>
caused it to descend sharply.  </TEXT>
