<HEAD>American Accused of Meteorite Theft Leaves Argentina</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An <LOCATION>Arizona</LOCATION> businessman charged
with trying to steal a 37-ton meteorite from a small Argentine town
left for home <DATE>Friday</DATE> after a judge ordered a 90-day postponement of
his trial.
   ``I've got my passport, and I'm out of here,'' <PERSON>Robert Haag</PERSON>, 33,
of <LOCATION>Tucson</LOCATION>, said in a telephone interview a few hours before
departure.
   ``I'm supposed to come back in 90 days,'' said <PERSON>Haag</PERSON>, also known
as the Meteorite Man. ``I'd like to come back and clear myself, but
I just don't know. Right now all I want to do is get back to my
business'' of selling meteorites.
   <PERSON>Haag</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Tucson</LOCATION> photographer <PERSON>Jeffrey Smith</PERSON>, 31, and <PERSON>Miguel
Fernandez</PERSON>, an Argentine, were arrested <DATE>Jan. 21</DATE> when they were
stopped by police near the small town of <LOCATION>Gancedo</LOCATION>, in <LOCATION>Chaco
Province</LOCATION>, 620 miles northwest of <ORGANIZATION>Buenos Aires</ORGANIZATION>.
   The three defendants were charged in the neighboring town of
Charata with the theft of the meteorite, roughly the size of a
small automobile, that police said they found in the back of a
tractor-trailer the men were driving.
   The meteorite, found in the <DATE>1960s</DATE>, reputedly is one of the
world's four largest. Charges against <PERSON>Smith</PERSON> were dropped and he
returned to <LOCATION>Tucson</LOCATION>.
   The area is rich in meteorites, and several years ago provincial
lawmakers made all meteorites provincial property and forbade their
unauthorized sale.
   Haag was released on <MONEY>$20,000</MONEY> bond but was forbidden to leave
<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>.
   Fernandez, unable to post <MONEY>$8,600</MONEY> bond, remains in custody in
<LOCATION>Charata</LOCATION>.
   Haag claimed he planned to purchase the meteorite in a deal
arranged by <PERSON>Fernandez</PERSON> with the owner of the land on which the
object had been found.
   But he expressed no regrets <DATE>Friday</DATE> over the outcome of the
expedition.
   ``This has been a super adventure,'' he said. ``I met a lot of
people in the <LOCATION>Chaco</LOCATION>, and at the end all kinds of them were trying
to sell me meteorites.''
   <PERSON>Haag</PERSON>'s case was being heard in Charata by <PERSON>Judge Juan Carlos
Clauter</PERSON>. The judge postponed the trial and returned <PERSON>Haag</PERSON>'s passport
on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> after <PERSON>Haag</PERSON> said he needed to return home to take care
of business.
   ``I'm losing at least <MONEY>$2,000</MONEY> a day by being here,'' said <PERSON>Haag</PERSON>,
who claims to do ``half a <MONEY>million dollars</MONEY> of business a year''
selling meteorites to private collectors, schools and museums.
   <PERSON>Haag</PERSON>, known to mineral enthusiasts back home as the Meteorite
Man, said he planned to sell the meteorite he is accused of trying
to steal. ``I could have gotten a <MONEY>million dollars</MONEY> for it,'' he said.
   If convicted, <PERSON>Haag</PERSON> could be sentenced to from 30 days to two
years in jail. If he fails to return when his trial resumes <DATE>May 13</DATE>,
he would forfeit his bail.
   Meteorites are common in the <LOCATION>Chaco</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Haag</PERSON> said, ``because a long
time ago a giant asteroid broke into millions of pieces, showering
the area with fragments, some the size of marbles and basketballs,
others weighing a ton or more.''
   The value of meteorites ``depends on the kind of material they
contain,'' he said. ``Some are fragments of the moon, others are
the heads of comets.''
   ``But I'm through dealing with meteorites in <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>,'' <PERSON>Haag</PERSON>
added. ``The last thing I want to do is to try to get anything out
of here.''
</TEXT>
