<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The International Monetary Fund approved a
$1.04 billion standby credit to Argentina to support the
government's economic program through 1992.
   At the request of the Argentine government, 25% of the IMF
funding will be set aside for debt reduction, the IMF said in
a statement.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s economic program is aimed at fostering
economic growth, rapidly reducing inflation and maintaining
an adequate level of international reserves.
   In fighting the country's periodic bouts of inflation,
Argentine authorities have frozen public-sector tariffs,
salaries and pensions, which led to a sharp decline in
inflation and interest rates in the <DATE>second quarter</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION>
said.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s economic program, supported by the standby
credit, also seeks to improve tax administration, reduce
staffing levels in the government, open up the economy to
international trade and further privatize public enterprises.
   The largest of these enterprises is the state oil company,
which is being trimmed in size for eventual privatization.
Price controls on petroleum products were eliminated in
<DATE>January</DATE> and parts of the company's operations have already
been sold.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> hopes to reschedule its official debt and to
normalize relations with commercial bank creditors, the <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION>
said.
   Separately, the <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION> agreed to provide <LOCATION>Tanzania</LOCATION> with <MONEY>$242
million</MONEY> to support its economic program through <DATE>June 1994</DATE>.
The program is aimed at fostering an average annual growth
rate of at least <PERCENT>4%</PERCENT>, while further reducing inflation.
<LOCATION>Tanzania</LOCATION> has been successful at working toward those goals
the past three years, the <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION> said.
   <LOCATION>Tanzania</LOCATION> also is seeking to open up its financial-services
sector to private investors, both domestic and foreign, and
to revamp its public financial institutions, the <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION> said.
   The <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION> money will be disbursed over three years, with
about <MONEY>$70.7 million</MONEY> available the first year in two
installments.
</TEXT>
