<HL> Argentina Continues Probe
Of Local Banks It Closed</HL>
<DD> 09/25/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> LATAM
BANKS, THRIFT INSTITUTIONS (BNK)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM) </IN>
<DATELINE> BUENOS AIRES (AP)  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Argentine central bank said it will continue investigating the six banks it closed, in the largest action taken by the state banking authority since President <PERSON>Raul Alfonsin</PERSON> was elected in <DATE>1983</DATE>, and will attempt to have them acquired by other financial institutions. 

   The central bank said the six banks were closed <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> because of "the serious deterioration of their solvency and liquidity" and "fraudulent administration." 
The closings were expected because the banks had been under investigations since as long ago as <DATE>December 1984</DATE>. 

   The biggest of the closed banks is <ORGANIZATION>Banco del Oeste</ORGANIZATION>, the 16th-largest institution in the country. 
The bank has 54 branch offices nationwide, and its deposits a year ago totaled <MONEY>$55 million</MONEY>. 
The other banks closed were <ORGANIZATION>Banco del Argense</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Banco de Credito Rural Argentino</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Banco del Iguazu</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>San Miguel Cooperativo Limitado</LOCATION> and Libertadores Cooperativo Limitado. 
They range in size from the 38th-largest to the 155th-largest in the country, though the size of their deposits wasn't immediately known. 

   Holders of accounts at the closed banks were told to go to the central bank to make claims for withdrawals, which are guaranteed by law. 

   Acquiring banks must try to assure the jobs of the closed banks' employees, the central bank said. 
But the uncertainty surrounding that situation caused the 2,400 employees affected by the closings to refuse to leave the banks yesterday. 

</TEXT>
