<HEAD>British Troops Take Off In Practice Airlift For Falklands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIZE NORTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of British troops took off
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> on an 8,000-mile practice airlift to reinforce the
remote <LOCATION>Falklands Islands</LOCATION> garrison in the <LOCATION>South Atlantic</LOCATION>.
   The first of up to 10 transport planes carrying 900 troops
departed at about <TIME>10 p.m.</TIME> from <ORGANIZATION>Brize Norton Royal Air Force</ORGANIZATION> base,
60 miles northwest of <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, said a <ORGANIZATION>Defense Ministry</ORGANIZATION> spokesman,
who was not identified in keeping with British custom.
   It was part of <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s controversial Fire Focus military
exercise, which marks <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s first major drill in the <LOCATION>Falklands</LOCATION>
since it won a <DATE>1982</DATE> war with <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> over the islands. The 25-day
exercise began <DATE>March 7</DATE>.
   Phantom fighter jets and other planes will fly in from other
British bases, <ORGANIZATION>Royal Air Force</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Michael Hill</PERSON> said.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>, backed by other Latin American nations, has called
the <MONEY>$690 million</MONEY> troop movement ``aggravating.'' <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> insisted
it is defensive.
   In the <LOCATION>Falklands</LOCATION>, Gen. <PERSON>Neil Carlier</PERSON> told reporters at <LOCATION>Mount
Pleasant</LOCATION> airport ``it is much cheaper to mount an exercise like
this than to hold a vast number of people down here at taxpayers'
expense which might also, perhaps, send out the wrong signals.''
   <PERSON>Carlier</PERSON> called the nature of the exercise misunderstood and said
the airlift was needed because ``we've just set up in a new base
and not yet had the opportunity to prove the system for having
reinforcements.''
   The 2,000 troops stationed on the <LOCATION>South Atlantic</LOCATION> archipelago
were placed in a state of high readiness to prepare for the arrival
of the reinforcements <DATE>Thursday</DATE> and <DATE>Friday</DATE>, he said.
   The reinforcements will include troops taking the role of the
enemy. Advance personnel, equipment and reporters arrived <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   Britain built the airport after the <DATE>1982</DATE> war to accommodate
wide-bodied jets which could be used to rush troops there in the
event of a build-up of tension in the region.
   In <DATE>1982</DATE>, Argentine forces invaded the islands. Lack of a
suitable runway forced <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> to form a naval task force that took
weeks to reach the islands.
   Britain recaptured the colony after a 74-day conflict which
killed 712 Argentines, 255 Britons and three <LOCATION>Falkland Islands</LOCATION>
civilians.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>, 200 miles west of the islands, claims it inherited
the Falklands from Spanish colonial days and that they were stolen
by <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>, which has ruled them as a colony since <DATE>1833</DATE>.
   The 1,900 islanders, most of British descent, say they prefer
British rule.
   This month, the <ORGANIZATION>Organization of American States</ORGANIZATION> voted 25-0 to
urge <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> to reconsider the exercise. The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>St.
Lucia</LOCATION>, a former British colony, abstained.
</TEXT>
