<HEAD>Thatcher Says Falklands Exercise `No One Else's Business'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister <PERSON>Margaret Thatcher</PERSON> said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> that
<LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s current military exercise to reinforce the <LOCATION>Falkland
Islands</LOCATION> against possible attack by <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> was ``no one else's
business.''
   Flatly rejecting protests by <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and other Latin American
countries, <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION>House of Commons</ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> had
a right and also ``a duty to see that reinforcement proposals could
in fact be carried out.''
   ``It is no one else's business except the defense of people's
rights in the <LOCATION>Falkland Islands</LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON>Mrs. Thatcher</PERSON>.
   About 900 troops will travel 8,000 miles next week to the
<LOCATION>Falkland Islands</LOCATION> from <PERSON>Brize Norton</PERSON> air base, north of <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, as
part of the exercise, called Fire Focus.
   The exercise began this week with mythical ``intelligence
reports'' warning that <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> was preparing again to invade the
south <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> archipelago which it has long claimed. The 1,800
British-descended islanders fiercely reject Argentine rule.
   Fire Focus is the first major maneuver announced by <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>
since it recaptured the islands from invading Argentine troops in a
74-day war in <DATE>1982</DATE>.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> has said it gave notice last month to <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> of the
intended exercise and has since announced that Fire Focus will
involve fewer than 1,000 men.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> maintains a garrison, reportedly of about 2,000 men, on
the islands and says it must practice sending in reinforcements in
order to avoid keeping more troops there permanently.
   Briefing reporters at <PERSON>Brize Norton</PERSON> on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, Foreign Office
Assistant Under Secretary <PERSON>Robin Fearn</PERSON> said Fire Focus ``threatens
no one. It is entirely defensive.''
   ``Far from being a cause for concern, it is an integral part of
our policy of reducing tension,'' he added.
   He said the initial post-war garrison had been halved in recent
years after the completion of a new runway at the Falklands
capital, <LOCATION>Port Stanley</LOCATION>, which can take wide-bodied jets.
</TEXT>
