<HEAD>Falkland Islanders Divided About British-Argentine Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN LEONARD</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STANLEY, Falkland Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Falklanders have mixed feelings
about talks on restoring relations between <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>,
which made their rocky, windswept archipelago a battleground seven
years ago.
   Most residents see negotiations as inevitable, but many fear a
deal that could cost them their British status. The first round is
scheduled for <DATE>Oct. 17-18</DATE> in <LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION>.
   About 1,800 people live on the bleak islands 300 miles east of
<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s tip. The main occupations are fishing and grazing sheep
on the chill moorlands.
   ``I think it's a bit worrying, really,'' said <PERSON>Nancy Poole</PERSON>.``How
far will they go? If they carry on, <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> will think <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> is
saying yes to a transfer of sovereignty eventually, I would think.''
   <PERSON>Mrs. Poole</PERSON> is secretary of Desire the Right, the only organized
political party. It hs taken no official position on the talks and
<PERSON>Mrs. Poole</PERSON> said her views were personal.
   <PERSON>Charles Keenleyside</PERSON>, an elected member of the islands' executive
and legislative councils, welcomeed the talks.
   He said a briefing by <PERSON>William Fullerton</PERSON>, the colonial governor,
convinced him ``we are not moving into a situation where items are
being discussed that are specifically against the wishes of the
Falkland Islanders.''
   Keenleyside added, however, that many people oppose any
resumption of links with <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and have deep suspicions about
the negotiations.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> invaded the British colony, which it calls the
<LOCATION>Malvinas</LOCATION>, in <DATE>April 1982</DATE> and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> sent a naval force that expelled
the invaders in a 74-day war that cost nearly 1,000 lives. The
Argentines claim the islands under rights dating from Spanish
colonial days.
   Attempts to begin talks foundered on <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s refusal to
negotiate the sovereignty of the islands. They are beginning now
because <PERSON>Carlos Menem</PERSON>, <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s new president, agreed to set the
sovereignty issue aside.
   Most islanders trust Prime Minister <PERSON>Margaret Thatcher</PERSON>'s
determination not to negotiate the islands away, but some wonder
what will happen when she leaves office.
   Senior magistrate <PERSON>Rosie McIlroy</PERSON> is grateful for movement.
   ``I'm glad to see there are talks because it seems to me that the
stalemate that existed before could not benefit anyone,'' she said.
``I do think some form of link with <LOCATION>South America</LOCATION> for the <LOCATION>Falkland
Islands</LOCATION> is necessary.''
   Issues at stake include shipping, air and communications links
with <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>, all severed since the war.
   Many islanders want no connections at all. They remember the
decade before the war, when the Argentine air force operated the
first regular air service to the islands and its ticket office in
<LOCATION>Stanley</LOCATION> was an intelligence outpost.
   When their troops landed, Argentine commanders had detailed
military and civilian knowledge of the islands.
   ``<LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>, OK,'' shop owner <PERSON>Peter Short</PERSON> said about
the talks, then added: ``Falklands and <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>, no.''
   <PERSON>Brian Summers</PERSON>, commercial officer for Cable and Wireless, said of
Menem: ``This man is far too smart. He is going to say all the right
things to the right people.''
   By playing down the sovereignty issue, he suggested, <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>
could gradually restore links of all kinds with the islands until
the transfer of sovereignty became inevitable.
   <PERSON>Joe Newell</PERSON>, a former farm manager, took the view that ``we're
going to have to deal with them sometime,'' and lawyer <PERSON>Kevin
Kilmartin</PERSON> said: ``It's quite obvious that <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>
should talk to each other.''
   <PERSON>Kilmartin</PERSON> said he hoped <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> would allow the Falklands
government to make policy in those areas of particular concern to
the islanders.
   Among the thorniest issues is protection of fish stocks in the
<LOCATION>South Atlantic</LOCATION>, where Argentine and Falkland fishing zones abut.
   Islanders also want <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> to stop influencing other South
American nations to deny access to a Falklands passenger and cargo
ship, which now may operate only to <ORGANIZATION>Punta Arenas</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
