<HEAD>Argentina, Britain Resume Consular Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> resumed
consular ties on <DATE>Thursday</DATE> after a nearly eight-year gap that dated
back to the <LOCATION>Falkland Islands</LOCATION> War.
   <PERSON>Alan Hunt</PERSON> presented his credentials to the <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION> and
was accepted as <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s consul. A similar ceremony took place in
<LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, where <PERSON>Santos Goni</PERSON> was accredited as the Argentine consul.
   Since the <DATE>1982</DATE> war, which <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> launched to recover
territory in the <LOCATION>South Atlantic</LOCATION> it has claimed since the <DATE>last
century</DATE>, each country has maintained only an interest section in
the other: <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> at <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s embassy in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> at the
<ORGANIZATION>Swiss Embassy</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Buenos Aires</LOCATION>.
   Consular flags will be hoisted in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Buenos Aires</ORGANIZATION> on
<DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   The way was paved for a thaw in relations by the election of
<PERSON>Carlos Menem</PERSON> as <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s president last <DATE>May</DATE>. Menem dropped the
government's previous insistence that ownership of the Falklands be
an issue in any bilateral talks.
   The countries have agreed to resume air and maritime
communications and lift all remaining commercial and financial
restrictions and restrictive practices imposed since <DATE>1982</DATE>.
   They also agreed to an umbrella clause that protects their
respective claims to sovereignty over the islands, which are
inhabited by 1,800 people, mostly British descendants.
   A further meeting in <DATE>February</DATE> is expected to lead to resumption
of full diplomatic relations.
   Buenos Aires surrendered to a British task force on <DATE>June 14,
1982</DATE>, 74 days after invading the <LOCATION>South Atlantic</LOCATION> archipelago.
</TEXT>
