<HEAD>Peronist Candidate Demands Argentine Sovereignty over Falklands</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICENTE L. PANETTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential candidate <PERSON>Carlos
Menem</PERSON> of the opposition <ORGANIZATION>Peronist Party</ORGANIZATION> was quoted on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> as
saying the <LOCATION>Falkland Islands</LOCATION> belong to <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and will be
recovered ``even if we must suffer the spilling of blood.''
   ``<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> will not give in,'' <PERSON>Menem</PERSON> said during a campaign
swing <DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>, according to <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s two independent news
agencies, <ORGANIZATION>Diarios y Noticias</ORGANIZATION> and Noticias Argentinas.
   The Malvinas _ <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s name for the territory off its south
coast that it has claimed since <DATE>1810</DATE> _ ``will return to form part of
the national territory even if we must suffer the spilling of
blood,'' he was quoted as saying.
   Menem was on a visit to <LOCATION>Ushuaia</LOCATION>, 2,045 miles south of the capital
city of <ORGANIZATION>Buenos Aires</ORGANIZATION>.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> went to war over the sparsely populated,
windswept and virtually treeless islands in <DATE>1982</DATE>. Argentine troops
invaded on <DATE>April 2</DATE>. A British expeditionary force recovered the
islands after a counterattack in which 712 Argentine and 255 British
soldiers died.
   The war lasted 74 days. <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> surrendered but refused to
formally declare an end to hostilities. Neither side resumed
diplomatic relations.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s claim dates to <DATE>1833</DATE>. It has since fortified the islands
and enforced a 200-mile zone of exclusion around them. <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> has
tried to isolate the islands commercially by prohibiting direct
flights or ships from the mainland.
   It has tried to apply international pressure to force <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> to
negotiate the islands' sovereignty. British Prime Minister <PERSON>Margaret
Thatcher</PERSON> has refused.
   The two agencies also quoted Menem as saying: ``I don't know how
much time will pass or how much blood we will have to spill to see
that the <LOCATION>Malvinas</LOCATION> return to Argentine territory.''
   President <PERSON>Raul Alfonsin</PERSON> and Foreign Minister <PERSON>Dante Caputo</PERSON>, who
also is president of the <ORGANIZATION>U.N. General Assembly</ORGANIZATION>, have said <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>
inherited the islands upon declaring independence from <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION>, and
the government will try to recover them peacefully through
negotiation.
   Ownership is an article of faith here. Argentine maps identify
the islands as the <LOCATION>Malvinas</LOCATION>, and schoolchildren are taught they were
stolen by <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>.
   Recovering the <LOCATION>Falklands</LOCATION> is a main foreign policy theme of
political groups from both left and right, along with the 4
million-member <ORGANIZATION>General Labor Confederation</ORGANIZATION> which backs <PERSON>Menem</PERSON>.
   Menem in the past said he would seek the islands' recovery by
diplomacy if he wins election on <DATE>May 14</DATE>. It was not known whether he
was speaking rhetorically in <LOCATION>Ushuaia</LOCATION>, or shifting and hardening his
position.
   A telephone call seeking comment from the British Interests
Section at the <ORGANIZATION>Swiss Embassy</ORGANIZATION> rang repeatedly but was not answered.
</TEXT>
