<HL>
   International:
   Menem Cabinet
   Shuffled After
   Currency Dives
   ----
   By Thomas Kamm
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
01/30/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   The two main watchdogs over Argentina's fragile economy
resigned after a massive run on the national currency.
   The resignations of Economics Minister Antonio Erman
Gonzalez and Central Bank Governor Javier Gonzalez Fraga
followed a 20% plunge in the value of the austral against the
U.S. dollar on Monday. The austral's plummeting fortunes --
it's down 40% so far this month -- is likely to translate
into a burst of inflation, undermining Argentina's shaky
economic recovery, economists say.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The resignation of <PERSON>Mr. Gonzalez</PERSON>, nicknamed "Superman" for
his initial success in cutting inflation, underlines the
continued instability of <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s politics and economy.
<PERSON>Mr. Gonzalez</PERSON>, an ally of President <PERSON>Carlos Menem</PERSON>, was viewed
abroad as a courageous minister. His resignation is a new
setback for <PERSON>Mr. Menem</PERSON> at a time when the president is trying
to contain damage caused by a short-lived military rebellion
last month, an unpopular amnesty granted to several of
<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s former military rulers and accusations by the
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> ambassador of government corruption.
   A presidential spokesman said Foreign Minister <PERSON>Domingo
Cavallo</PERSON>, a Harvard-trained economist, will succeed <PERSON>Mr.
Gonzalez</PERSON>, becoming <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s fourth economics minister
since <PERSON>Mr. Menem</PERSON> took office 19 months ago. <PERSON>Mr. Gonzalez</PERSON> will
be the new defense minister.
   Argentine authorities closed banks and financial markets
yesterday, but said they would reopen today. Messrs. <PERSON>Cavallo</PERSON>
and <PERSON>Gonzalez</PERSON> gave a joint news conference <TIME>last night</TIME> and <PERSON>Mr.
Cavallo</PERSON> pledged to pursue <PERSON>Mr. Menem</PERSON>'s unpopular free-market
policies, including privatization of state companies and
trade liberalization, while seeking to bring down the
overvalued austral in order to boost production and exports.
   While <PERSON>Mr. Menem</PERSON> spent most of the day in conferences with
<PERSON>Messrs. Gonzalez</PERSON>, <PERSON>Cavallo</PERSON> and other top officials, scenes of
confusion filled the country. Cash machines ran out of bills
as they were raided by Argentines caught off-guard by the
bank closure. The federation of small shopkeepers urged
members to stay closed during the bank holiday because of
price uncertainty. Other stores raised prices by as much as
<PERCENT>40%</PERCENT>. The price of meat at the Liniers cattle market, the
country's biggest, rose by <PERCENT>30%</PERCENT> yesterday.
   Although the size and swiftness of the austral's nose dive
was a surprise, the market had been signaling its displeasure
with the artificially low exchange rate for some time. While
it succeeded in reducing inflation -- the consumer price
index has been below two digits for three months and fell to
<PERCENT>4.7%</PERCENT> in <DATE>December</DATE> -- the low rate created huge problems for
industrial exporters and farmers, who recently threatened to
stop paying taxes because of their declining revenue.
   President <PERSON>Menem</PERSON> reportedly asked conservative economist
<PERSON>Roberto Alemann</PERSON> to become <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s seventh central bank
president in 18 months. If <PERSON>Mr. Alemann</PERSON> accepts, a clash looms
with <PERSON>Mr. Cavallo</PERSON>. <PERSON>Mr. Alemann</PERSON>, who twice served as
<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s economy minister, reportedly wants autonomy for
the <ORGANIZATION>Central Bank</ORGANIZATION>, which regulates interest rates, the money
supply and transfers to heavily indebted provincial banks.
</TEXT>
