<HEAD>British, Argentine Officials Open Talks on Falklands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British and Argentine officials opened two
days of talks <DATE>Thursday</DATE> on issues related to the disputed <LOCATION>Falkland
Islands</LOCATION>, a step toward restoring full diplomatic ties, embassy
spokesmen said.
   An <ORGANIZATION>Argentine Embassy</ORGANIZATION> official who spoke on condition of
anonymity said <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> would ask <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> to drop the 150-mile
military ``protection zone'' around the Falklands, which <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>
calls the <LOCATION>Malvinas Islands</LOCATION>.
   The zone has been enforced since <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> invaded the <LOCATION>South
Atlantic</LOCATION> islands in <DATE>1982</DATE>. The Argentine soldiers were driven off by
British troops after a 74-day war.
   Britain now requires Argentine military ships to request and
receive British permission before entering the zone.
   The talks <DATE>Thursday</DATE> were held at the Argentine ambassador's
residence in central <LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION>. On <DATE>Friday</DATE>, the talks will move across
the street to the <ORGANIZATION>British Embassy</ORGANIZATION>.
   A <ORGANIZATION>British Embassy</ORGANIZATION> spokesman said details of the meetings were
not expected to be made public.
   The talks serve as a preliminary step to high-level meetings in
<LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION> on <DATE>Feb. 14-15</DATE> that will be aimed at restoring full
diplomatic relations.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> has claimed the islands since declaring independence
from <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> in <DATE>1816</DATE>. British claims to the islands are based on
effective occupation since <DATE>1833</DATE>.
   Relations between the two countries have improved considerably
since <DATE>October</DATE>, when two days of talks in <LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION> ended with the
restoration of consular relations and an agreement to move toward
normal diplomatic and economic relations.
   Since then, <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> has allowed British vessels and planes to
operate freely in Argentine territory, and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> has lifted a
restriction on the navigation of Argentine merchant ships in the
150-mile military protection zone around the <LOCATION>Falklands</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s five-man delegation at this week's talks was led by
<PERSON>Adrian Beamish</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Office</ORGANIZATION>'s assistant undersecretary of
state for the <LOCATION>Americas</LOCATION>.
   The Argentine side was headed by <PERSON>Jose Maria Otegui</PERSON>,
director-general for the <LOCATION>Malvinas</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
