<HEAD>Britain Hopes for Better Relations with Argentina</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Office Minister <PERSON>Tim Sainsbury</PERSON> said <DATE>Friday</DATE>
that <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s new president appears to be seeking ``more
normal'' relations, and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> will respond positively.
   ``I hope we can look forward to a period of tangible achievement
in our relations with <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>; that's certainly our aim,''
<ORGANIZATION>Sainsbury</ORGANIZATION> told the <ORGANIZATION>House of Commons Friday before Parliament</ORGANIZATION>
adjourned for the <DATE>summer</DATE> recess.
   <ORGANIZATION>Sainsbury</ORGANIZATION>, under questioning from a legislator, refused to say
if Argentine President <PERSON>Carlos Menem</PERSON> has sought to reopen
negotiations with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> over the disputed <LOCATION>Falkand Islands</LOCATION>, off
the coast of <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>, and the restoration of diplomatic relations.
   ``It is a very delicate matter. You would not expect me to go
into details at this stage,'' said <ORGANIZATION>Sainsbury</ORGANIZATION>. ``But you may rest
assured that we will respond positively to any proposals consistent
with our commitment to the Falkland Islanders.''
   He said <PERSON>Menem</PERSON>, who took office <DATE>July 8</DATE>, apparently seeks improved
relations while while putting aside the ``delicate issue'' of
sovereignty over the <LOCATION>Falklands</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> invaded and occupied the British colony in <DATE>1982</DATE>, but
British forces recaptured the islands in a 74-day war.
   After the war <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> promised the 1,600 Falklands residents,
most of whom are of British descent, that it would not negotiate
the issue of sovereignty.
   Previous attempts to improve relations have foundered on the
question of sovereignty.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> wants to normalize trade relations with <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>,
negotiate a fishing agreement, re-establish air links and reduce
tension. That could lead to a reduction of the costs of maintaining
a British military garrison on the islands.
   During the debate <ORGANIZATION>Conservative Party</ORGANIZATION> legislator <PERSON>Ray Whitney</PERSON> said
<PERSON>Menem</PERSON> had created a ``distinct and new atmosphere which we must
seize and take advantage of.''
   ``We cannot miss the opportunity which is now opening up,''
added <PERSON>Whitney</PERSON>, who was chairman of the governing Conservatives'
foreign affairs committee during the war for the <LOCATION>Falkland Islands</LOCATION>,
known in <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> as the <LOCATION>Malvinas Islands</LOCATION>.
   He said new diplomatic moves would disturb the islanders, who
want to maintain the present status, but their long-term interests
``can only be guaranteed by a different set of relationships''
between <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
