<HEAD>First Direct Air Links Since 1982 Falklands War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> resumed
direct air links <DATE>Saturday</DATE> for the first time since the <DATE>1982</DATE>
Falkland Islands War, the latest in a series of moves to
re-establish their historically strong ties.
   An <ORGANIZATION>Aerolineas Argentinas</ORGANIZATION> flight took off from <LOCATION>Buenos Aires</LOCATION>
<DATE>Saturday</DATE> <TIME>evening</TIME>, and a <ORGANIZATION>British Airways</ORGANIZATION> jetliner left <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> 2{
hours later en route to this South American capital. Both were to
arrive <DATE>Sunday</DATE>.
   ``We're planning a little celebration'' for the arriving British
airliner, said <PERSON>Ian Gillespie</PERSON>, regional manager for <ORGANIZATION>British Airways</ORGANIZATION>.
``Six pipers from the <ORGANIZATION>Buenos Aires St. Andrews Society</ORGANIZATION> of the <ORGANIZATION>River
Plate</ORGANIZATION> will pipe the passengers off.''
   The two countries severed relations after <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> invaded the
<LOCATION>South Atlantic</LOCATION> islands, claiming it inherited the archipelago from
<LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> upon declaring independence in <DATE>1810</DATE>.
   Britain counterattacked and recovered the sparsely populated
territory of sheepherders and fishermen, which it has ruled since
<DATE>1833</DATE>.
   The issue of sovereignty blocked talks for years. Since taking
office in <DATE>July</DATE>, President <PERSON>Carlos Menem</PERSON> backed improved ties with
<LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and temporarily set aside _ without giving up <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s
claim _ the issue of ownership.
   Trade and travel restrictions were lifted 9nOctober. Interest
sections were upgraded to consulates last month. Shipping ties
resumed earlier this month.
   Talks set for <DATE>February</DATE> in <LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION> will mark ``a decisive stage
toward renewing diplomatic relations between <LOCATION>Great Britain</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>,'' <PERSON>Menem</PERSON> said last week.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> was once one of <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s main trading partners, with
substantial landholdings and interests in the South American
county's meatpacking industry.
   By resuming direct flights, <ORGANIZATION>Aerolineas</ORGANIZATION>' Britain-bound flights
will continue to <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> from <LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION>, where passengers had been
dropped off and picked up by <ORGANIZATION>British Airways</ORGANIZATION>.
   British Airways' Argentina-bound flights will continue to <ORGANIZATION>Buenos
Aires</ORGANIZATION> from <ORGANIZATION>Rio de Janeiro</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Sao Paolo</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>, where passengers
had been dropped off an4 Licked up by <ORGANIZATION>Aerolineas</ORGANIZATION>.
   Nonstop direct flights will be possible when <ORGANIZATION>Boeing</ORGANIZATION> 747-400s are
brought into service, <PERSON>Gillespie</PERSON> said. He said about 25,000
passengers fly the route each year.
</TEXT>
