<HEAD>Argentina, Britain Agree to Renew Diplomatic Relations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with quotes, more terms of
agreement, details. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FRANCISCO CONDE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> agreed <DATE>Thursday</DATE> to
restore full diplomatic relations nearly eight years after they
fought a 74-day war over the <LOCATION>Falkland Islands</LOCATION>.
   After two days of talks in <LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION>, the announcement was read in
Spanish by Lucio del Solar, ambassador at large for <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>, and
in English by Sir <PERSON>Crispin Tickell</PERSON>, British ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION>United
Nations</ORGANIZATION>.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> agreed to lift a 150-mile military protection zone it
has enforced around the <LOCATION>South Atlantic</LOCATION> islands since a task force
sent by Prime Minister <PERSON>Margaret Thatcher</PERSON> defeated Argentine
invaders in <DATE>June 1982</DATE>.
   New security arrangements for the archipelago 300 miles off
<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s southeast coast, which are home to about 1,900 people
and thousands of sheep, are to involve advance notice by both sides
of military maneuvers in the area.
   The presence of an estimated 2,000 British soldiers at <LOCATION>Mount
Pleasant</LOCATION> outside <LOCATION>Port Stanley</LOCATION>, the Falklands capital, was not
mentioned in <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s agreement, although <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> had
previously called for a reduction.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> also agreed to consult on relations
between the <ORGANIZATION>European Economic Community</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Latin America</LOCATION>, and to
establish a <ORGANIZATION>Working Group on South Atlantic Affairs</ORGANIZATION>.
   In <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd</ORGANIZATION> said of the agreement:
``It underlines the fact that we have no quarrel with <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>,
and this has been achieved without any sacrifice of sovereignty. So
it's a very good agreement and I hope it's a turning point and will
lead to a new relationship.''
   President <PERSON>Carlos Menem</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> told reporters in Buenos
Aires: ``Everything is resolved. Aside from having eliminated _
definitively, I believe _ the possibilities of an armed conflict,
it opens wide possibilities for us in the ... <ORGANIZATION>European Economic
Community</ORGANIZATION>.''
   <PERSON>Javier Perez de Cuellar</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>U.N.</ORGANIZATION> secretary-general, declared:
``I very much welcome the decision by both governments to
re-establish diplomatic relations. This immediately creates an
atmosphere of confidence.''
   The battle for the <LOCATION>South Atlantic</LOCATION> islands, which <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> calls
the <LOCATION>Malvinas</LOCATION>, cost the lives of 712 Argentines, 255 Britons and
three islanders. Dissatisfaction over the war, which <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s
military government claimed to be winning until shortly before the
surrender, contributed to the end in <DATE>1983 of nearly eight years</DATE> of
military rule.
   <DATE>Thursday</DATE>'s agreement stiplulated that talks would continue on
fishing rights and that the <ORGANIZATION>International Red Cross</ORGANIZATION> would arrange
visits by Argentines to war cemeteries in the <LOCATION>Falklands</LOCATION>.
   Garcia del Solar called the accord ``very satisfactory,'' and
<PERSON>Tickell</PERSON> said the decision to end the military zone by the end of
<DATE>March</DATE> ``set a new base for relations between our two countries.''
   ``There is no secret understanding, no confidential
memorandum,'' he said. ``It's all here.''
   A breakthrough in <DATE>October</DATE> provide for renewed consular ties,
resumption of air and maritime links and moves toward lifting all
trade restrictions.
   By mutual consent, the latest talks did not touch on sovereignty
claims.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> says it colonized the islands in <DATE>1766</DATE> when <PERSON>John MacBride</PERSON>
founded <LOCATION>Port Egmont</LOCATION>. <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> gained control but permitted the British
to remain until <DATE>1774</DATE>, then abandoned the islands when it ceased to
govern <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> in <DATE>1810</DATE>.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> traces its claim in the Treaty of <LOCATION>Tordesillas</LOCATION>, which
assigned New World territories to <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Portugal</LOCATION> in <DATE>1494</DATE>. It
says the British occupied the islands by force in <DATE>1833</DATE> when Capt.
<PERSON>John Onslow</PERSON> expelled the Argentine population.
</TEXT>
