<HEAD>Argentine Lawmakers Declare Falklands Part of Argentina</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OSCAR J. SERRAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> voted
<DATE>Thursday</DATE> to claim the <LOCATION>Falkland Islands</LOCATION>, eight years after losing a
war with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> over the remote <LOCATION>South Atlantic</LOCATION> archipelago.
Britain immediately objected to the measure, which appeared to be
largely symbolic.
   The legislation, approved despite opposition by <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s
foreign ministry, declares the Falklands _ known in <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> as
the <LOCATION>Malvinas</LOCATION> _ to be part of the new Argentine province of <ORGANIZATION>Tierra
del Fuego</ORGANIZATION>. It also covers the Sandwich and <LOCATION>South Georgia</LOCATION> islands,
also British possessions.
   In <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION>British Foreign Office</ORGANIZATION>, speaking
on condition of anonymity, said: ``We don't accept this or any
other Argentinian claim to British territory.''
   The <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> has already approved the legislation, and President
<PERSON>Carlos Menem</PERSON> was expected to sign it.
   <PERSON>Menem</PERSON> said the measure ``does not signify that <LOCATION>England</LOCATION> recognize
our sovereignty, but rather, simply, that we ratified the Malvinas
are ours.''
   He added he did not expect the move to ``cause obstacles'' in
relations with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> has held the Falklands since <DATE>1833</DATE>. In <DATE>1982</DATE>, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> fought a 74-day war over the windswept islands, causing
the deaths of nearly 1,000 men.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s ruling Peronist party had pushed for the inclusion
of the Falklands in the legislation creating the new province.
However, critics warned that the measure could backfire.
   They said the move could hamper <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s continuing claims of
sovereignty by giving credence to British arguments that <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>
might try to impose its will on the 1,900 islanders.
   The islanders are British subjects and say they prefer to remain
so.
   For seven years after the war, <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> refused to formally
declare a cessation of hostilities. Diplomatic ties were severed
and relations handled through third countries. Commerce, trade,
travel and investment declined.
   Improving ties was one of <PERSON>Menem</PERSON>'s top foreign policy goals after
he became president last <DATE>July</DATE>. Consulates were upgraded to
embassies, direct air travel resumed, and a military exclusion zone
around the islands lifted.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> restored full diplomatic relations <DATE>Feb.
16</DATE>, following two days of talks between the two countries in <LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> agreed to lift a 150-mile military protection zone
enforced around the islands since <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> invaded them in <DATE>June
1982</DATE>.
   The agreement said new arrangements to ensure the security of
the islands would involve advance notice by both sides of military
maneuvers in the area.
   By mutual assent, their agreement did not touch on the two
countries' conflicting claims to the <LOCATION>Falklands</LOCATION>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>British Foreign Office</ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> said: ``The
recent progress made on British-Argentine relations was only
possible on the understanding that we were not willing to discuss
sovereignty. And we will be repeating our views via diplomatic
channels.''
   The new province was created in response to demands by Argentine
residents of the island of Tierra del Fuego for greater government
representation. It had been <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s lone territory.
   <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> shares ownership of the island at the foot of <LOCATION>South
America</LOCATION>. The dividing line between <LOCATION>Chile</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> was extended
years ago through <ORGANIZATION>Tierra del Fuego</ORGANIZATION>.
   Under the measure, residents of the new province would elect a
governor, who is now appointed by the president. Representation in
the national <ORGANIZATION>Chamber of Deputies</ORGANIZATION> would double to four, and two
<ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> seats were to be alloted.
   The provincial capital is to be <LOCATION>Ushuaia</LOCATION>, 2,260 miles south of
<PERSON>Buenos Aires</PERSON> and the southernmost city in the world.
</TEXT>
