<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MS <ORGANIZATION>Zelia Cardoso de Mello</ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s economy minister, has signed a Dollars
350m (Pounds 205.8m) loan agreement with the <ORGANIZATION>Inter-American Development Bank</ORGANIZATION>
(IADB), writes <PERSON>Stephen Fidler</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
The loan, to improve urban sanitation, will create about 45,000 jobs. It had
been delayed because of <LOCATION>US</LOCATION> concern over <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s growing arrears with
commercial banks.
The loan was approved by the bank's board last week, following an agreement
in principle last month with leading bank creditors over the arrears. Ms
Cardoso yesterday met <PERSON>Mr Michel Camdessus</PERSON>, managing director of the
<ORGANIZATION>International Monetary Fund</ORGANIZATION>.
She told journalists she hoped <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> could 'start as soon as possible'
negotiations over its external debt and hoped the <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION> and other institutions
would provide 'necessary support' for the process.
Asked about the possibility of debt relief for <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> from creditor
governments, she said she did not want to anticipate any proposal - which
would have, in any case, to follow agreement with the <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION>. However, <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>
applauded the decision to write off at least 50 per cent of <LOCATION>Poland</LOCATION>'s debts
and said the treatment 'should be extended to other middle- and low-income
countries'.
The <LOCATION>US</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION> have agreed to lead a support group of countries friendly
to <LOCATION>Peru</LOCATION> to help it erase its Dollars 2.1bn in arrears to the <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION>
and <ORGANIZATION>Inter-American Development Bank</ORGANIZATION>. This would allow borrowing from the
institutions to resume.
Agreement came at a meeting on <DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME> in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Mr Camdessus</PERSON>
said another meeting would take place in <DATE>May</DATE>, at which other countries
friendly to <LOCATION>Peru</LOCATION> would be present, to take the issue forward.
The size of the arrears in relation to <LOCATION>Peru</LOCATION>'s resources complicates the
problem. <PERSON>Mr Camdessus</PERSON> also said he hoped the <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION> would provide support for
programmes in <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>.
