<HEAD>Argentine Foreign Minister Says Will Meet With British Colleague</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreign minister said <DATE>Thursday</DATE>
he will meet with his British counterpart next week in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> to
discuss restoring diplomatic and commercial ties severed at the
outbreak of the <DATE>1982</DATE> Falkland Islands war.
   It would be the first meeting between Argentine and British
foreign ministers since the 74-day war in the <LOCATION>South Atlantic</LOCATION>, which
left dead nearly 1,000 people.
   Foreign Minister <PERSON>Domingo Cavallo</PERSON> said his meeting with Foreign
Secretary <PERSON>John Major</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> will take place <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> at <ORGANIZATION>U.N.</ORGANIZATION>
headquarters in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>.
   Cavallo will fly to <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> on <DATE>Saturday</DATE> with President <PERSON>Carlos
Menem</PERSON>, who is scheduled to address the <ORGANIZATION>U.N. General Assembly</ORGANIZATION>.
   Argentine and British diplomats are scheduled to meet <DATE>Oct. 17-18</DATE>
in <LOCATION>Madrid</LOCATION> to discuss renewing diplomatic and trade relations.
   Such a move would in effect set aside for now the dispute
stemming from their rival claims of sovereignty over the <LOCATION>Falklands</LOCATION>.
   The islands off <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> have been ruled by <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> since <DATE>1833</DATE>.
<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> claims it inherited the territory, which it calls the
<LOCATION>Malvinas</LOCATION>, when it declared independence from <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> in <DATE>1810</DATE>.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> invaded the islands, inhabited by about 1,800 people of
British descent, on <DATE>April 2, 1982</DATE>. Britain counterattacked and
defeated <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> in a war that helped contribute to the downfall
of the military junta that ruled from <DATE>1976</DATE> until <PERSON>Raul Alfonsin</PERSON> was
elected president in <DATE>1983</DATE>.
   Alfonsin, who by law could not run for re-election, was succeeded
in <DATE>July</DATE> by <PERSON>Menem</PERSON>, who defeated <PERSON>Alfonsin</PERSON>'s candidate, <LOCATION>Cordoba</LOCATION> Gov.
<PERSON>Eduardo Angeloz</PERSON>, in the general election.
</TEXT>
