<HEAD>New Long-Term Conditions Set For Argentinian Loans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new, long-term way of dealing with the <ORGANIZATION>Third
World</ORGANIZATION>'s crippling <MONEY>$1.2 trillion</MONEY> debt may be foreshadowed by <MONEY>$700
million</MONEY> worth of new loans the <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION> is offering to <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>.
   On the surface, <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> seems a poor prospect for more loans.
   It already owes more than <MONEY>$49 billion</MONEY>, the biggest debt of any
Third World country after <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>.
   It should be paying <MONEY>$4.5 billion</MONEY> this year in interest alone,
and already is about <MONEY>$1 billion</MONEY> behind in its payments. With
interest rates rising, the bill may be <MONEY>$1 billion</MONEY> higher next year.
   The financial world is so skeptical about the prospects for
repayment that Argentine loans can be bought for less than <MONEY>22 cents</MONEY>
on the dollar.
   Finance Minister <PERSON>Juan Sourrouille</PERSON> says he hopes to pay half the
interest out of the country's own earnings. The rest he will have
to borrow, presumably from many of the same banks that lent the
original money.
   President <PERSON>Raul Alfonsin</PERSON>'s government, the first one freely
elected after years of military rule, faces an election in <DATE>1989</DATE>.
Many of his opponents, who are given an excellent chance to succeed
him, are talking about suspending interest payments altogether.
   Yet the 151 governments in the <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION> probably will approve
the new loans next month. The bank's sister organization, the
<ORGANIZATION>International Monetary Fund</ORGANIZATION>, has been negotiating all <DATE>summer</DATE> with
the Argentine government to make another <MONEY>$1.2 billion</MONEY> in loans.
Sourrouille says negotiations should be completed in a couple of
weeks, and he then will know how much to ask from the commercial
banks _ probably more than <MONEY>$1 billion</MONEY>.
   Why all this new lending? It has a lot to do with an old
banker's saying:
   ``Lend a man a thousand dollars and he's in your power; lend him
a million and you're in his.''
   The lenders keep on lending in the hope that <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and the
other big debtors will use the money wisely, investing in new
factories and farm equipment so they can earn more money from their
exports and catch up with their bills. It's called ``growing out of
financial difficulties.''
   The lenders, all represented at the current fund and bank
meetings in <LOCATION>Berlin</LOCATION>, see no other choice. The fund says the strategy
is working well, and that the debtors' exports are growing faster
than their debts.
   New loans are given under conditions usually tied to economic
policies. If the borrower fails to meet them, the disbursements are
cut off.
   Traditionally, the <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION> has taken the lead in setting the
conditions, providing a ``seal of approval'' for other creditors.
But the fund was set up originally to deal with short-term currency
problems. The <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION> is intended to aid long-term development
of poor countries.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> is considered a ``middle-income'' country, with
individual earnings averaging <MONEY>$2,370</MONEY> a year _ compared with <MONEY>$120</MONEY> in
<LOCATION>Ethiopia</LOCATION> and <MONEY>$21,250</MONEY> in <LOCATION>Switzerland</LOCATION>.
   But <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> has fallen on hard times and incomes have been
declining through the <DATE>1980s</DATE>. So the country is considered a
candidate for basic improvements.
   Now, for the first time, the <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION> has taken the lead in
setting conditions, and many of them are conditions on long-term
policy of a kind that the <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION> would not require.
   Sourrouille not only has promised to cut government spending
sharply, but also is undertaking other changes basic to his
country's economy.
   He has promised the <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION> he will strengthen the tax
administration, reducing tax evasion and improving collections. He
is attempting to improve the bank system, making the major public
banks self-sustaining rather than dependent on government
subsidies, and has promised new policies on trade and industry.
   There has been some grumbling. <PERSON>Nigel Lawson</PERSON>, the British
chancellor of the exchequer, has warned against easing the
conditions for loans.
   The <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION> accord with <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> reportedly made some <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION>
people furious. But <PERSON>Michel Camdessus</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>IMF</ORGANIZATION> managing director,
welcomed the agreement publicly.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and the fund are expected to agree on further
conditions. Commercial banks presumably will come in with their
loans, including new money for investment in <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>. The hope is
that the new policies will put the country back on the road to the
kind of prosperity it enjoyed before World War II.
   If they do, the new leadership by the <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION> may furnish a
model for other countries in long-term trouble.
</TEXT>
