<HEAD>Britain, Argentina Open Talks on Restoring Ties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After seven years of silence, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> began talks aimed at normalizing diplomatic
and trade relations that were severed after the <DATE>1982</DATE> Falklands War.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>U.N.</ORGANIZATION> ambassador, Sir <PERSON>Crispin Tickell</PERSON>, met <PERSON>Lucio Garcia</PERSON>
del Solar, director-general of <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Foreign Ministry</ORGANIZATION>, to
``seek to establish the conditions and agenda for direct talks
between the <LOCATION>United Kingdom</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>,'' according to <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s
<ORGANIZATION>U.N.</ORGANIZATION> mission.
   The mission said the meetings ``will be without prejudice to the
sovereignty positions of either side regarding the <LOCATION>Falkland
Islands</LOCATION>.''
   The talks opened <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> but no details on the times and
locations were disclosed. An official communique is expected after
they conclude <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   Although the dialogue is not taking place under <ORGANIZATION>U.N.</ORGANIZATION> auspices,
``it is an encouraging development that Secretary-General <PERSON>Javier
Perez de Cuellar</PERSON> welcomes,'' said his spokesman, <PERSON>Francois Giuliani</PERSON>.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s new president, <PERSON>Carlos Saul Menem</PERSON>, made the dialogue
possible when he dropped his country's insistence that <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>'s
claim to the islands it calls the Malvinas be the first step in any
talks.
   A meeting between British and Argentine government officials in
<LOCATION>Bern</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Switzerland</LOCATION>, in <DATE>July 1984</DATE> broke down when <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> raised the
sovereignty issue as a precondition.
   In <DATE>April 1982</DATE>, <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> invaded the islands, where 2,000 people
of British descent live. Britain counterattacked and defeated
<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> in a six-week war that cost nearly 1,000 lives.
   Britain cut ties with <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and has said it will never
negotiate sovereignty of the islands, where the population has
expressed almost unanimous preference for continuing their colonial
relationship with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> have held indirect talks through the <LOCATION>United
States</LOCATION> on such issues as fish conservation.
   Menem's government would like to recover fishing rights in the
area around the <LOCATION>Falklands</LOCATION>. Britain currently enforces a 150-mile
exclusion zone, steering Argentine vessels away from the area.
   Many nations fish in the areas just outside the exclusion zone,
largely unregulated, and <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> would like to reach
an accord on regulating fishing in the south <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION>.
   Both countries have lifted bans on importing each others'
products, with <PERSON>Buenos Aires</PERSON> taking the step this month. <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>
lifted its ban in <DATE>1985</DATE>.
   Diplomats said <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> is also looking ahead to the unified
<ORGANIZATION>European Community</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1992</DATE> and realizes it must mend fences with
<LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>, which will be one of the major members of the new
Euromarket, the largest trade bloc in the world.
   The <LOCATION>Falkland Islands</LOCATION> are 300 miles east of the <ORGANIZATION>Strait of Magellan</ORGANIZATION>.
   A British explorer sighted them in <DATE>1592</DATE>, and Britons landed on
them in <DATE>1690</DATE>. They have been under British rule since <DATE>1833</DATE>, but
<LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> claims it inherited the land when it declared independence
from <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> in <DATE>1810</DATE>.
</TEXT>
