<HL> U.S. Ex-Im Bank Eases
Argentine Access to Credits</HL>
<DD> 04/21/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> GOVMT LATAM
BANKS, THRIFT INSTITUTIONS (BNK)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON) </IN>
<DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Export-Import Bank</ORGANIZATION> eased restrictions on export credits to <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>. 

   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> governmment export-credit agency said that starting <DATE>May 1</DATE> it will consider direct loans or guarantees of private credits with maturities of up to seven years to <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> for the purchase of <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> goods and services. 
The bank stopped approving new credits and loan guarantees to <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> in <DATE>1982</DATE>, when the country got involved in a war with <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> over the <LOCATION>Falkland Islands</LOCATION>. 

   Last <DATE>December</DATE>, the bank decided to authorize credits and loan guarantees with maturities of one year or less to help <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> buy commodities and industrial equipment from <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> suppliers. 

   <PERSON>John Bohn</PERSON>, president of the Export-Import bank, said that while <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> is a "heavily debt-burdened" country, it also is a sizable market for <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> goods and services. 
He said "we are encouraged" by the Argentine government's economic-adjustment efforts. 

   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials said the decision to ease restrictions on credits to <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> was prompted by the willingness of commercial banks to come to an agreement with the South American country on refinancing of its external debts. 
They said the action had nothing to do with the Argentine government's success in quelling a mutiny among some military officers over the weekend. 

   The bank currently has about <MONEY>$700 million</MONEY> in loans outstanding and guarantees covering earlier credits to <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>. 

</TEXT>
