<HL> Brazil Hardens
Its Position
On Paying Debt
---
It Tells Banks Not to Repay
Creditors Seeking Recall
Of Short-Term Credit
---
By Roger Cohen and Peter Truell
Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 02/26/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> LATAM
BANKS, THRIFT INSTITUTIONS (BNK)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON) </IN>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> ordered its commercial banks not to repay foreign banks that seek to recall short-term credits and deposits at the Brazilian institutions. 

   The decision, communicated in a telex from the central bank, represents a hardening of <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s position. 
It came amid increasing signs in <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> that the new debt moratorium -- initially dismissed by some bankers as no more than a tough bargaining stance -- is in fact a carefully prepared and committed attempt to change the terms for discussion of <LOCATION>Latin America</LOCATION>'s huge debt. 

   In the telex, <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> said that if foreign banks ask for their money back, Brazilian banks should pay the funds to the central bank. 

   Foreign banks lend <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> about <MONEY>$15 billion</MONEY> in short-term trade credits and money-market deposits. 
The Brazilian government fears there might be a run on these credits and deposits following its unilateral suspension of interest payments on about <MONEY>$67 billion</MONEY> of foreign debt last <DATE>Friday</DATE>. 

   The measure, announced in a telex signed by <PERSON>Carlos Eduardo de Freitas</PERSON>, the director of the central bank's foreign department and Antonio de <PERSON>Padua Seixas</PERSON>, director of the bank's foreign-debt department, was aimed particularly at small and medium-sized <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> banks, Brazilian sources said. 
Some of these have already shown signs of wishing to cut the loans. 
Their severance -- the most obvious way they have of immediately retaliating to the moratorium -- could seriously disrupt the Brazilian economy, which is the eighth-largest in the <LOCATION>West</LOCATION>. 

   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> and international bankers were unhappy to learn of the move second-hand, through friends at Brazilian banks and news reports. 
<LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> planned late yesterday to send a telex explaining its move to international banks. 
<PERSON>Mr. Seixas</PERSON> was in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> yesterday, and international bankers complained to him about the lack of official notification. 
"There were a lot of unanswered questions at the meetings," said one <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> banker. 

   <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s finance minister, <PERSON>Dilson Funaro</PERSON>, who is the architect of the debt moratorium, is due in <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION> soon and seems guaranteed a frosty reception. 
Brazilian sources, who requested anonymity, said the minister would be in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> tomorrow to visit with <PERSON>Paul Volcker</PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION>Federal Reserve Board</ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION>Treasury</ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON>James Baker</PERSON>. 
Other sources said <PERSON>Mr. Funaro</PERSON> will go to <LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> following his <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> visit and later will go to <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>. 

   Whatever his itinerary, he has succeeded in offending the creditors. 
"He can carry on his populist line of blaming the banks, but sooner or later, people are going to realize that the problems are <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s own policies," said a senior <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> banker who requested anonymity. 

   <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s ambassador to <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Marcilio Marques Moreira</PERSON>, was more conciliatory, saying that the telexed instruction on short-term credits "is intended to be transitory and is to ensure that these credits remain stable over the coming weeks of negotiations." 

   Further signs emerged, meanwhile, that <PERSON>Mr. Funaro</PERSON> is intent on confrontation with creditors over the total <MONEY>$108 billion</MONEY> that <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> owes foreign banks, governments and international agencies. 

   Argentine sources said <PERSON>Mr. Funaro</PERSON>'s meeting <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> with <ORGANIZATION>Argentine Treasury</ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON>Mario Brodersohn</PERSON> was devoted largely to examining how <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> could help <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> if the latter faced international retaliation for a prolonged debt moratorium. 
Two questions examined were what goods <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> could guarantee <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> if other sources were cut off, and how <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> could be used as a transit point for Brazilian exports and imports. 

   Argentine Economics Minister <PERSON>Juan V. Sourrouille</PERSON> yesterday said that Brazilian primary goods destined to be incorporated into Argentine exports will temporarily be allowed automatic and unrestricted entry into <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION>. 
That statement accompanied the announcement of measures to fight a surge in inflation and eliminate distortions in the Argentine economy, including a devaluation of the Argentine currency and a four-month wage and price freeze. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Brodersohn</PERSON> has expressed support for the Brazilian stand, saying that <LOCATION>Argentina</LOCATION> also could suspend interest payments if its demands for new money are not met. 
The two countries, traditional rivals, joined in a broad attempt to strengthen trade, financial and political ties through a pact signed last year. 

   The exchange with <PERSON>Mr. Brodersohn</PERSON> -- along with <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s stockpiling of oil and wheat, and its transfer of assets to places unreachable by creditors -- suggests that <PERSON>Mr. Funaro</PERSON> is preparing for a long moratorium. 
Officials close to him say he is in no mood to compromise, either on returning to the International Monetary Fund or on his insistence that a long-term accord be found that slashes the current level of <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>'s interest payments. 

   In this context, a growing number of people in <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> believe his statement must be taken seriously that <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> will save <MONEY>$5.6 billion</MONEY> if the moratorium lasts until year's end. 

</TEXT>
